My strategy was to simply reply that I do not know or do not remember when I was asked questions that might implicate me in the crime. When I was asked questions that I believe would not implicate me in the crime, or for which I had real memories from that day unrelated to the crime, I told the interviewer as much as I could.

If I remember things right, when I read the cognitive psychology course I learned that what makes peoples stories of true memories different from made up stories is that the stories of true memories is much more detailed. I therefor had as a strategy to say nothing that was untrue since a made up stories could be identified as such because of its lack of detail. When I got questions about my activities that might implicated me in the crime, I stated that I do not remember. At the same time I saw no reason of not answering questions when I believed the answer to them would not implicate me in the crime. When I got a question of my activities that I believed could not implicate me in the crime, I described my memory in detail. I also made sure not the describe the places I went to to commit the crime in greater detail than other areas of the building, since I thought this might implicate me.

I did not think that I could convince the interviewer that I was innocent, but I had a strategy for not implicating myself. I have heard that individuals involved in organized crime in Sweden have a strategy of not saying anything at all in police interviews, in order to be able to come up with the (to themselves) most beneficial testimony after information has been presented to the court by police investigators and other suspects. If I would commit a crime I therefor think that the safest strategy in an interview would be to not say anything at all. I also think that the risk of me providing information to the police that could be used against me is greater than the chance that anything I say could be beneficial to me.
